{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13902"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13902"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.53,0.07,0.23,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of nausea and light-headedness. He has a medical history of oesophageal adenocarcinoma, for which he underwent an oesophagectomy three months ago. At the time of surgery, CT and PET scans showed no evidence of metastatic disease. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has a slightly unsteady gait but no other focal neurological deficits. A CT brain is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellar abscess","Cerebellar metastasis","Cerebellar infarction","Cerebellar haemorrhage","Primary cerebellar tumour"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT image shows a well-defined, hyperdense lesion in the right cerebellar hemisphere, which is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E. Given the patient\u0027s history of oesophageal adenocarcinoma, even though previous staging scans were negative, this is the most likely diagnosis. Metastatic disease can develop rapidly, and the brain is a potential site for oesophageal cancer metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a wedge-shaped area of hypodensity that conforms to a vascular territory. The well-circumscribed, rounded appearance of this lesion is not typical for an infarct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary cerebellar tumour\u003C/strong\u003E, such as a medulloblastoma or hemangioblastoma, is less likely in this age group and clinical context. Primary brain tumours are generally less common than metastases in adults, especially those with a known primary cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more acute symptoms, fever, and often a history of recent infection or immunosuppression. The CT appearance would usually show a ring-enhancing lesion with surrounding oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would appear hyperdense on CT, similar to what is seen in this image. However, a haemorrhage would typically present with more acute and severe symptoms, and would not be the most likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s history of cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presenting symptoms of nausea and light-headedness are consistent with a cerebellar lesion, which can affect balance and coordination. This case highlights the importance of maintaining a high index of suspicion for metastatic disease in patients with a history of cancer, even when initial staging scans are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebellar metastases can present with nausea and light-headedness due to increased intracranial pressure.","Oesophageal cancer can metastasise to the brain, even after curative-intent surgery.","CT imaging is crucial for diagnosing brain metastases in patients with a history of cancer presenting with neurological symptoms."],"references":["Kothari N, Hoffe S, Frakes J, et al. Outcomes in patients with brain metastasis from esophageal carcinoma. J Gastrointest Oncol. 2016;7(4):562-469. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4963374/","Verstegen M, Harker M, van de Water C, et al. Metastatic pattern in esophadeal and gastric cancer: Influenced by site and histology. World J Gastroenterol. 2020;26)29):6037-6046. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7584055/","Smirniotopoulos J, Jager H. Differential diagnosis of intracranial masses. Diseases of the brain, head and neck. Spine 2020-2023. IDKD Springer series. Available at: https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-38490-6_8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13902"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20837"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20837"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XpqH34lIkdycseH3Lx1zzacbvuGjMT.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XpqH34lIkdycseH3Lx1zzacbvuGjMT.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1200,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T11:08:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-11T09:03:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh